SIMPLE: tumultuous
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Tumultuous
<hw>Tu*mul"tu*ous</hw> <pr>(t⟦usl⟧*m⟦ucr⟧l"t⟦usl⟧*⟦ucr⟧s)</pr>,
<pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>tumultuosus</ets>: cf. F.
<ets>tumultueux</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Full of tumult;
characterized by tumult; disorderly; turbulent.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The flight became wild and <qex>tumultuous</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Conducted with disorder; noisy; confused;
boisterous; disorderly; <as>as, a <ex>tumultuous</ex> assembly or
meeting</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Agitated, as with conflicting passions;
disturbed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His dire attempt, which, nigh the birth⟦br⟧
Now rolling, boils in his <qex>tumultuous</qex> breast.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Turbulent; violent; <as>as, a <ex>tumultuous</ex>
speech</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Disorderly; irregular; noisy; confused;
turbulent; violent; agitated; disturbed; boisterous; lawless; riotous;
seditious.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Tu*mul"tu*ous*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> --
<wf>Tu*mul"tu*ous*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tumulus</ent>⟦br⟧
\'d8
